# Retro Realism Tennis (Working Title) — One-Page Game Brief

## 1) Core Vision
**Game fantasy:** realistic tennis decision-making and shot selection, presented with a retro 1990s/8-bit visual and audio style.

**Current goal:** quick prototype (not polished release yet).

**Target match length:** ~3–5 minutes.

## 2) MVP Clarified (What “smallest playable version” means)
**MVP = the tiniest version that is still fun and complete enough to play repeatedly.**
For your game, MVP in 1–2 weeks means:
- 1 player character vs 1 CPU opponent
- 1 court
- Basic scoring flow (start match → points/games → winner screen)
- Serve + rally loop with core shot types
- Keyboard controls
- Minimal retro visuals/SFX placeholders

If this works and feels good, you expand from there.

## 3) Platform & Tech Direction
- **Primary target:** Web + Desktop
- **Engine choice:** **Godot** (recommended for your experience level and fast prototyping)
- **Multiplayer plan:** Single-player first; design code so local/online multiplayer can be added later

### When to start using Godot
Start **immediately** for Milestone 0 (project setup). Do not wait for “final art.”
Use placeholder sprites and focus first on controls + ball + scoring.

## 4) v1 Scope (Based on Your Answers)
### In Scope (Prototype v1)
- Single-player mode
- Modes: **Exhibition** and simple **Tournament**
- 2 characters total
- 1 court
- 5 difficulty levels with light rubber-band behavior
- Retro-inspired UI (readable text, simple menus)
- Energetic chiptune direction with placeholder audio

### Out of Scope (Prototype v1)
- Full online multiplayer
- Voice umpire system (future stretch goal)
- Advanced accessibility assists
- Large roster/court count

## 5) Gameplay Design
## Control Philosophy
- Minimal inputs, but advanced shot outcomes.
- Movement should feel smooth and responsive (not stiff), while maintaining retro readability.

## Shot System (Requested)
### Serves
- Flat serve (middle behavior)
- Topspin serve (one side behavior)
- Slice serve (other side behavior)

### Groundstrokes
- Flat (middle/default)
- Topspin
- Slice

### Volleys
- Flat
- Topspin
- Slice

### Baseline Utility
- Lob available from baseline contexts

## 6) AI & Difficulty
- **AI style:** fun rallying + occasional outwitting, not perfect robot play
- **Difficulty count:** 5 levels
- **Rubber-band:** yes (lightly applied in prototype)
- **Opponent personality:** yes, distinct tendencies per opponent

## 7) Retro Art/Audio Direction
### Visual references
- Mario Tennis feel + classic tennis flash game simplicity
- Old-school Pokémon color vibes (borrowed style, not strict hardware emulation)
- GBA-era-ish sprite scale and simple animation counts

### Art constraints (initial)
- Limited palette per scene (Pokémon-like color restraint)
- Small player/ball sprites at GBA-like readability scale
- Modest animation frames (only what is needed for clarity)

### Audio direction
- Energetic chiptune music
- Key SFX: serve impact, rally hits, player grunts, crowd cheer
- Umpire score callouts: future addition

## 8) Production Reality (Simplified)
You said “just for fun” and “$0 budget,” so this plan assumes:
- Mostly self-made or free placeholder assets
- Free/open-source tools
- Fast iteration over polish

### Asset plan for prototype
- **Create now:** basic placeholders (player, ball, court markers, UI text)
- **Source later (optional):** free retro SFX/music packs if needed

## 9) Success Criteria (Your Version)
The prototype is successful if:
- You are having fun playing repeated matches
- Controls feel tight and understandable within ~30 seconds
- Match flow works end-to-end in ~3–5 minutes
- Game runs smoothly on your target machine

